==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English [[bagage]], from Old French [[bagage]], from [[bague]] "bundle", from Germanic (compare [[bag]]).  

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈbæɡɪdʒ/}}, {{SAMPA|/"b{gIdZ/}}, {{AHD|băg'ĭj}}

**'''Hyphenation:''' bag·gage
**'''Rhymes:''' [[Rhymes:English:-æɡɪdʒ|-æɡɪdʒ]]

===Noun===
'''baggage''' (''uncountable'')
# [[luggage]], especially in a metaphorical or negative sense: ''emotional baggage''
# {{idiom}} {{vulgar}} heavy baggage; women and children.  Also a familiar epithet for a woman; as, cunning baggage, wanton baggage, &c.

